{"title":"DR Loss: Improving Object Detection by Distributional Ranking","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"One-stage object detectors suffer from severe inter-class imbalance (many background vs. few foreground anchors) and intra-class imbalance (only a few hard negatives), while focal loss reweights per-anchor heuristically and ignores per-image structure.","method":"Convert per-anchor classification into an image-dependent ranking task and introduce Distributional Ranking (DR) loss that ranks, with a margin, the expectations of per-image positive and negative score distributions instead of all O(n^2) pairs. Derive these distributions by solving a KL-regularized optimization that ‘pushes’ scores toward the decision boundary while preserving diversity, yielding closed-form, image-dependent soft weights that emphasize harder examples (q− ∝ exp(p/λ−), q+ ∝ exp(−p/λ+)). Optimize a smooth logistic surrogate with margin γ=0.5, which reduces pair complexity to a single pair (ĤP+, ĤP−) per image and enables direct recovery of standard classification."},{"problem":"Training the proposed non-convex DR loss efficiently and stably across different mini-batch sizes requires guidance on optimizer behavior and calibration back to classification.","method":"Provide an SGD convergence result for DR loss under µ-smoothness with convergence rate O(1/√(mT)) and derive a batch-size-aware learning-rate scaling η ∝ √(m/T) with η ≤ 1/µ. Further, show that setting the ranking margin to γ=0.5 recovers the standard 0.5 classification threshold, enabling a plug-and-play replacement of focal loss in RetinaNet without architectural changes."}]}
